The paper proposes a new framework for Adversarial Imitation Learning (AIL) that improves the quality of reinforcement signals by weighing the adversarial reward with a confidence score from support estimation of the expert policy. This involves machine learning techniques such as support estimation, adversarial learning, and reinforcement learning. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.RO (Robotics). The paper also presents empirical results on benchmark control tasks, which suggests that it may also belong to cs.SY (Systems and Control) and cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-categories.
